==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|applaudere||to clap the hands together, applaud}}, from {{m|la|ad||to}} + {{m|la|plaudere||to strike, clap}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/əˈplɔːd/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/əˈplɔd/}}
* {{a|cot-caught}} {{IPA|en|/əˈplɑd/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-applaud.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɔːd}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[applause|Applause]]; applauding.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[plaudit|Plaudit]].

====Related terms====
* {{l|en|applause}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[express]] [[approval]] (of something) by [[clap|clapping]] the [[hand]]s.
#: ''After the performance, the audience '''applauded''' for five minutes''.
# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[praise]], or express approval for something or someone.
#: ''Although we don't like your methods, we '''applaud''' your motives.''
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare Pericles|II|v|34|passage=Now by the Gods, I do '''applaude''' his courage.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 10, 2011|author=David Ornstein| title=Arsenal 1 - 0 Everton| work=BBC Sport| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/16015017.stm| passage=It moved him to within one goal of {{w|Thierry Henry}}'s 34 in 2004 and Henry - honoured with a statue outside the stadium on Friday - rose from his seat in the stands to '''applaud''' Van Persie.}}

